    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, sorry about the confusion! I was just trying to say that adding cold water is like giving a goblin a cold bath to calm them down before they start causing trouble. The heat was probably too high, making the proteins in the yolks clump up like a bunch of goblins trying to fit into a tiny hat.\n\nTo fix it, you need to add **one or two extra egg yolks** (depending on how much sauce you have) that are **room temperature or slightly cool**, never boiling hot. Warm yolks are too eager to cook and will just make the mess worse, while cold yolks act like a shock to the system, helping to re-stabilize the emulsion. Whisk them in slowly while keeping the pan off the heat entirely. If you're too eager and add them too fast, you'll just end up with a greasy puddle again, which is exactly what happens when you try to rush a goblin into a line.\n\nIf that doesn't work, you can try the \"butter trick\": take a tiny bit of the broken sauce, mix it with a little fresh cold butter, and whisk that mixture into the main pot. It's like bribing a g",
